main event: A photographer took photographs of an unidentified flying object (UFO) near South Charleston, Ohio on October 31, 1964.
interesting points: The photographer took multiple photos of the same scene, with slight changes in exposure time.
The strange objects were not visible to the photographer at the time of exposure, and no sounds were heard.

Photo analysis indicates the images were likely caused by a series of exposures prior to film loading or after removal from the film clip holder, resulting in a superimposed image from a housed light source.
The sharpest image was probably caused by a light with a reflector and screen, similar to common ceiling lighting.
The photographer did not want the images released to the news until the investigation was completed, as the photographer believed it was not 'trick photography'.
result: inconclusive, likely caused by photographic anomalies
photographs: yes, multiple photographs and a negative were provided for analysis
